nf Hague. The question of .Japanese im\nmigration into Canada has been settled.\n\"MALIGN INFLUENCE\nOF POLITICS.\"\nHas Been Felt In The Boston Fire De\npartment Says Report of The Fi\nnance Commission Given\nLast Night\nBoston, Jan. 29. In a report of nearly\nR 000 words, t he finance commission\nwhich is making an investigation of til\ndepartments of the city of Boston, has\nIssued its findings on trie tire depart\nment. There are no radical measures\nsuggested or severe condemnations in\nthe report.\nThe commission find.-s that \"since May\ner Collins'\" death, the department hai\nfallen under the \"malign influence of\npolitics,\" and that tire mayor has usurp1\ned to a great extent, the power of ap\npointment which belongs to the head\nof the department exclusively, and that\npolitical preferment has been exercised\nin making appointments, in some eac\nto the detriment of the department. The\nefficiency of the clerical force i declared\nto be low. The commission places it\nself on record as opposed to the one day\noff in five, with pay, as causing a cost j\nof $80,000 annually, resulting last year\nin a deficit of $40,000.\nOn the whole, however, the commis\nsion finds that tire department is in a\nsplendid state of' efficiency, auove the\naverage, that the habits of the men are\ngood, the rumors of thefts at fires by\nfiremen and of intoxication' unfounded,\nthe apparatus in good shape and the\nservices rendered of high grade.\nTho commission recommends among\nother things that hot coffee be rved the\nfiremen at tne large tires irt cold weather\nat the expense of the department.\nIn closing its report the commission\nrecommends among other tilings:\nThe jjnmeJinte and permanent divorce\nof all political considerations from this\ndepartment; strict enforcement of the\nrule forbidding political activity or\njoining political clubs by the firemen,\nand a yearly test of appliances.\nThe finance commission derlares that\nthe invest igation has disclosed evidence\nof a combination among certain manu\nfacturers of rubber tires, which the com\nmission intend to submit to the I'niteJ\nStates district attorney.\nAUTOMOBILE RECIPROCITY.\nLOVERS' QUARREL\nENDED IN TWO DEATHS\nYoung Man Had Remonstrated With the\nCtrl Who Came From the Old\nCountry to Marry\nHim.\nritUhurg, Ta., Jan, 29. A quarrel be\ntween two lovers at Ambridge, war here,\nlast night ejided in the death of both,\neach indicting a fatal wound upon the\nother. The victim were Mary Cozzitri,\n18 years o!d and strikingly 'beautiful,\nand Dominic Polcina, 2,3 rears old. Their\ncourts-hip began in Italy and he came\nto America three years ago to prepar\na home, tending for the girl last Octo\nber. Polciim is said to have been most\njealous from the day of her arrival, and\nwhen she delayed the wedding from time\nto time he became frantic.\nLast night he visited the cirl at the\nhome of her sister. They talked a few\nminutes ami the girl fled from the kitch\nen to her own room on the third floor\nlocking herwelf in. Polcina followed ami\nbroke open the door. A struggle fol\nlowed. Evidently the cirl had prepared\nto defend herself. An instant later t.ir\nwas a shriek and a heavy body fell.\nIt was that of Polcina. A delicate, keen\nedged knife the girl was known tiyhv,\nin her room was found near him. The\nblade had been thrust into hi ear, pierc\ning his brain.\nhiwt bs he fell Polcina fired a' shot\nfrom his revolver. The bullet entered\nthe girl's side. She ran down the two\nflights of stains ami fell dead on the\nkitchen floor. Other in tho house rush\ned to the upstairs room where Polcina\ndied just after they reached him.\nIt is presumed that Polciiwi, after\nnreaKing iiro uie gin s room, nail threat\nened to shoot lier and that she then\nstnhlicd him ami attempted to run\nawav.\nC0RTELY0U\nON DEFENSE\nClaims Credit For Avoiding\nBig Financial Panic\nTHAT FAVORITISM CHARGE\nWATERBURY CELEBRATES.\nSecretary of the Treasury To-day Made\nReply to the Senate's Inquiry as\nto the Ground for His Action\nin the Crisis.\nBIG FIRE IN CHICAGO\nRAGED THREE HOURS\nLast Night's Loss Is Estimated at More\nThat a Million Dollars Third\nDisastrous One Within Three\nDays.\nChicago, Jan. 29. The third disastrous\nfire in the business district of the city\nin as many days caused a lose last night\nclimated at more than $1,000,000 in\nthe almost complete destruction of the\nbuilding at 144 abawh avenue, oeeu-\npiiHl by. Alfred Peats Co.. dealers in\nwall paper, the building adjoining it on\ntho south occupied by John A. Colby\nSon, f umit lire dealers, and that in the\nrear, fronting on Michigan avenue, oc\ncupied by the millinery firm of Edison\nKeith Co. Those to the north and\nsouth of the Keith building occuipod by\nage iirotners x lo. ami itteortore Ach-\nr Co., millinery firms, were damaged\nby fire and water. The fire started in\nthe engine room of the Peats building\nand raged for three hours.\nTl heaviest (osiers are: Peats\nCo.. .f-2.)0.000; John A. Colby Sons,\ntWiOO.WK); Cage Brothers, $25,)00; Theo\ndore Asdicr Si Co., $2\",000.\nWashington, D. C, Jan. 29. \"In every\nmeasure taken by the secretary, he feels\nthat he was found to have regard not\nsimply to the operations of the treasury,\nbut to their effect upon the financial\ncondition of the country. The present\nhead of the department has not assumed\nthis obligation willingly, and would lie\ngum to lie relieved of it. at least in part,\nhy suitable legislation.\" With ths\nwords, Secretary Cor t el you concluded bis\n15,000-ward reply to the Senate resolu\ntion of inquiry' justifying the radical\nmethod he used in meeting the recent\nfinancial panic.\nHe claims for his adminstration the\nfull credit for preventing a disastrous\nfinancial panic. He meets the clwtrge\nof favoritism in the distribution of bonds\nby producing records that they went to\n10 state, and the certificate\"! to eighteen\nstates, located in different, sections of\nthe country.. Public deposits were made\nto meet the business demand an! not\nmerely to accomm-vlafe the banks.\nHe notes recent withdrawal of $10.\n000,000 from the New York banks and\nsays that this \"will be followed bv a\ncall upon banks outside of New York,\nwhich will be based upon local condition\nrather than upon the payment of a fixed\npereejitage of their holdings of public\nmoneT.\"\nBoard of Trade Banquet Over New In\ndu3tries Secured.\nYVaterbury, Jan. 29. The annual\nmeeting and banquet of the Waterbury\nboard ot trade was liei.I at the v aier\nburv inn hist evening at 7:. Hi. The fo!\nlowing officers were elected: President,\nA. H. Smith: vice-president, E. V.\nHuntley; secretary, 11. C. Wliitehill;\ntieasurer. W. B. Clark. Following the\nehction Landlord Davis nerved one ot\nhis matchless banquets, there being\ncovers laid, and the following program\nwa,i very successfully cumcil out:\nt liaiinmn W. B. Clark\"; toastmaster, L\n0 Moodv: E. G. Miller, \"Developing\nNatural Resources:\" F. W. Reimberr.\n\"Our School;\" G, E. Moody, \"Progress!\nDr. f. K. Steele, \"invoices; lienry ,r.\nKemp, Impression of Waterbury: E.\nE. Campbell. \"Local Railroad Statistics\"\nS. C. Wheeler, \"Early History;\" S. S.\nGraves, \"One Thought.\"\nThe past mr has been the most suc\ncessful in the history of this organiza\ntion, several new industries having been\nlccated here and the VVaterbury inn\nnwde the pride of the town.\nDEATH OF AGED WOMAN.\nLITTLETON SUMS UP\nIN THAW'S DEFENSE\nMakes No Oratorial Pyrotechnics, But\nGives a Plain Staetment of the\nCase.\nANOTHER LARGE FIRE.\nLoss at Kansas City, Mo., Last Night\nWas Half a Million.\nKansas City, Mo., Jan. 2ft. Fir in\nthe canning department of one of the\ntwin main buildings of the packing plant\nof Nelson Morris Jt r-ompjiny, on the\nKaw river in Kansas City, Kansas- last\nnight, caused a loss est .i mated at half\na miMion dollars.\nSTOLE PARSON'S HAT.\nNow\nThe Rev. Mr. Gleason Declines\nCall to Deerfield, N. H.\nDeerfiohl, X. H., Jan. 29. The Pev.\nMr. (ileason of Imsdale, It. I., who had\nreceived a call from the First Baptist\nchurch here, 1ms declined to accept,\nmuch to the disappointment of the so\nciety. It is understood the reason is\nthis\":\nWhen Mr. Gleason preached here as\na candidate some woodchoppers who\nwere in attendance stole his oat and lie\nhad considerable difficulty in recovering\nit.\nHe was obliged to walk two miles o\na lumber camp where he induced the\nmen to surrender his properly.\nThe people of the church here ex\npress the hope that he has not judged\nl)eerfield Baptists by Deerfield wood\nchoppers and let the incident iufluepce\nhim in the call extended.\nMATTY BALDWIN WON.\nRhode Island Autoists Propose New\nLaw.\nProvidence, Jan. 20. The Rhode Is\nland automobile club propose new laws\nfor the control of machines and drivers.\nThe committee which drafted the pro\npofed act consisted of Frank W. Tilling\nhast, attorney J. Jerome Halm and Ju\nlian A. Chase.\nThe niavimum speed in compact pro\ntimts of cities and towns is placed at 15\nmiles an hour, the speed in other plan's\nto be at all times \"reasonable and\nrtroper,\" The fee for n automobile li\n,nie is increased from $2 ti $10, to be\nj,iied to the owner of a machine. whil-\ndm additional licen-e fee of $2 is charged\nf,-.r the driver of a machine.\nXl-p uni.ioe feature of the proposed\nJaw i reciprocity clause, placing the\njsrrie re-frictions upon non-re-i lent au\ntnV.ti;;-! as are implied upon Rhode\ni -'.in.ler-s when thee to another state.\ny.,r in-:arice the f-tate\nwinces that every automobile sh\nf New Jersey\n)bi!e shall be\nre it is\nt' a N\"'\" Jrrv aotomobilist comes to\nI 'tde I-nd h will 1 forced io pro\n5-,-ense before he can cro.s ti.e\ncure 1 j,.\ntiier ml' Lut.e L.iu4j.\nIn 12-round Bout in Boston Last Even\ning. Boston, Jan. 20.--Matty Baldwin of\nCharlestow-n wars given the decision over\nKid liixxlman of Boston at the end of\na 12-rourw! encounter at the Armory Ath\nletic association last night. The. battle\nwaa an interesting one with the su\nperiority slightly in Baldwin's favor.\nTERRIBLE DEED\nOF A YOUNG BOY\nBlew Off Hia Sister's Head With a\nShotgun and Then Strutted About\nas If Proud of His Act.\nRochester, N. Y Jan. 20. In the ab\nsence of his mother from home yester\nday afternoon William Mcllride, a 12-year-old\nboy of Egypt, n little place\nen-t of here, put on a belt of his father's\nloaded a shotgun with cartridge of\nbuckshot and blew the head off nis 4-ycar-old\nsi-ter, Viola, who ha bcei left\nby her mother strapped in a high chair.\nAn older sister, al.-vo ot home, told Cor\noner Ki'lip that the boy then strutted\nalxiut with the gun and even pointed it\nat her.\nAt last moved by the elder sister'\nfright, the boy took up the body, put\nit. into a blanket and carried it behind\na barn, where he hid it. When asked\nby the coroner hy lie di 1 mis, he said:\n\"Well, she was dead, and I thought she\nneeded to be in a cold place.\"\nThe mother, Mrs. Fnima McRriJe, is\na widow, and four of her eii'ht children\nsre in an in-titution i:i Buffalo. Her\nhusband whs killed some month ago in\na tram accident at FairpoiU\nNew York, Jan. 21). The announce\nment that Attorney Martin W. Little\nton would sum up this niorninir at\ntracted the largest crowd of the Thaw\ntrial to the court room. Evelyn sat\nbide her sister-in-law. Jlrs. Curneaie.\nand the latter' husband. .'i'lie Imt\nagain women was rais.1 tenipoi-anlv\nand several women friends of Littleton\nwere m the room. Among the pe;-ta-tors\nwas Sir Alan Johnson, Brit Wi niin\niter to Denmark. Littleton began his\npjKwh at 10:55 o'clock,\n\"An American verdict from this Amer\nican jury is all we want,\" said Littleton.\n\"We Udieve that you are convined fnm\nthe evidrnce that this defendant was\nnot of sound mind when he killed Stan\nford White. The prosecution wa com\npelled to prove that he ws sane at\nthe time of killing, but we were not\ncompelled to prove he was of unsound\nmind.\" (,'oing info proof of iirsanily,\nLittleton dwelt particularly upon Thaw\"'\nmentally tainted herilatel\nLittleton steered entirely clear of\n\"lemeiitia Amerii-ana\" and other rhe\ntorical pyrotecnnics. He combat ted the\ninsinuation of the state that the de\nfense of insanity was picked by him as\na subterfuge. His plea was plain in\nsanity, with no other argument than\nthat Thaw could not adjudged guilty\nbecause ot in mental incompetence,\nwhen he killed White.\nMr. Jerome's elimination of expert tes\ntimony from the rebuttal ease occasioned\nmuch talk. Based upon his assertions\not last year that I haw was an incurable\nparanoiac, rumor had it that tine prose\ntutor might not be disp!osed with a\nverdict of not guilty on the ground of\ninsanity, with an ensuing committal of\nHarry Thaw to the asylum for tho crim\ninal insane at Mattewan. Throughout\nthe trial, however, Mr. Jerome- hs (it\ntempted to belittle and di scroti it all tes\ntimony having to do with Thaw's irra\ntionality. He hits attempted to rfiow\nthat the youthful outburst of the de\nfendant were fits of temper which de\nserved a spanking,\" as- he expressed it,\nrather than scientific discussion. He has\nattempted to discredit the outbreaks in\nInter life with the suggestion that they\nwere the result of too much drink and\nnothing more.\nThat the prosecutor will ridicule the\nexpert testimony is generally agreed.\nHaving no cxiie-rts of hi own, he hits a\nf re hand in that direction this year. Mr.\nJerome's move yesterday also frustrated\na plan of the defense to call in sur\nrebuttal several of the experts who testi\nfied against Thow at. his hist trial but\nwho, when Mr. Jerome switched to the\nappointment of a lunacy commission,\nmade affidavits. Hvtting forth the opinion\nthat Thaw was so in-sane as to be in\ncapable of understanding the nature of\nthe proceedings agiiini-t him or of in\ntelligently advining with counsel.\nDIadema J. (Smalley) Noyes of Hyde\nPark Was 91 Years Old,\nHyde Park, Jan. 2D. Diadem J.\nSmsiHcy, the oldest person in the town\nof Hyde Park, widow of Lucius H.\nNoyes, died Tuesday morning of pneu\nmonia, after a few hours' iUijc. She\nwas about Monday and retired in her\nti-snal health that night. Mrs. Noyes was\n01 years old and the last of the grandchil\ndren of (.'apt. Jedediah Hyde, after whom\nthis town was tisimed. She was the\n(laughter of (apt, Francis Smalley, was\nImru in this town, and had always lived\nlu re. She is mirvived bv four children,\nMrs.. Waldo Brigham. Mr. H. W. Hul\nImrd ami Edward L. Xoyea of this place\nand A, B. Noyes of St. Jolmsbury. A\nlarge number of grandchildren and great\ngrandchildren also survive her. She was\na member of in Congregational church.\nThe funeral will take plant? at her lute\nhome Thursday afternoon at two o'clock, j\nESCAPED GUARD\n;i; AND GOT FREED0A\nMartin Manning of Bellows Falls Dupli-\ncated William Wright's Feat in\nWashington Last Summer.\nPratt leboro' Jan. 29. Martin Man\nning. who was taken to' Bellow Falls\nto Newfane jail Saturday to serve a sen\ntence of 3d days, escaped yesterday anj\nlias not been caught, although jailer\nKarl Daw received a report tmit Man\nning had been seen in East Dover, where\nIt asked the way to Wilmington. Man\nning was taken out yesterday for the\nfirst time with the prisoners who coin\npose the chopping gang and who are em\nployed by Sheriff A. H. Thompson in\nthe woihIs. He made an excuse to his\nguard John Fredotte. whereby he was\nallowed to get out of sigitt for a brief\ntime and lie immediately ran for his\nliberty. His trail was followed for some\ndistance atnoung the mountain.\nAN INQUEST.\nHELD TO-DAY\nOver Death of Alan Whose\nBody Was Found Yesterday\nIN WOODS NEAR SWANTON\nJAS. McCONACHIE DEAD.\nMan's Name Is Not Known But Ho Is\nThought to Have Been a Hun\ngarian Laborer on Railroad.\nBRYAN IN WINDOW ADDRESS.\nFor an Hour Held an Impromptu Recep\ntion Yesterday, v\nWashington, Jan, 20, In a w indow\nrecess of the wide hall in front of the\nsenate chamber William J. Bryan yester\nday for an hour, held an impromptu\nreception for senators and representa\ntives. The committee on finance was engaged\nin too final Consideration of the Aldrich\nfinancial measure., As Mr. Bryan came\nalong from the house talking animated\nly with a couple of congressmen; word\nwa-s passed to the Democrats of the fi\nmuice committee and Senator Bailer and\nSenator Teller emerged and greeted the\nNebra-kan. Retiring to the window\nniche an animated discussion took place\nbetween Senator Bailey and Mr.' Bryan,\nwith Senator Teller otienng an occasion\nal suggestion, and Kcprtsventtives\nHardy and Randall of Texas and James\nKerr, a prominent Pennsylvania Dem\nocrat, as listeners.\nMr. Bryan said later the discussion\nwas alwuit the Democratic view of the\ncurrency question.\nSwanton, Jan. 29. An inquest was\nheld to-day to determine the cause of\ntue death and to establish the identity\nof the man whose body was found in\nthe- woods north of this place yesterday.\nAs yet there is no identification of 'the\nman, but be is thought to have been a\nHungarian laborer. On the fly leaf of a\nprayer book which was found on his\nperson was a note showing that he had\nsailed from Bremen on August 10, but\nnot giving the year. There was no nam\non the book.\nA pay envelope which was numbered\n69 contained tint name of Jimi Hollar and\nthe date December, 1907. On the same.\nin rubber stamp, was -(iapl'ante\" which\nis tlumght to be a station on the Quebec\nisoutht'rn railroad. The belt of the cloth\ning was gone ana the ciotiiing wus\ntwisted, as if the body hud been thrown\nTha sum of $1.13 in Canadian moiiey\nSvas found in the pockets.\nme iKjity is now m the undertaking\nrooms oi Mmth TfJley here.\nThe small poplar stick with which th\nstrangling cord had been twisted had\nbeen broken from a near-by brush pile,\nThe ikad man's fate was lacerated and\nbruised, giving evidence of a struggle.\nThe place of the tragedy i marly\nnine jrorn ar;y tion.se xo cries were\nheard. In the man's pockets were found\na cotton shirt, several bandke-rchiefsv and\na piece of new cotton cloth carefully\nwrapper up.\nLast night State's Attorney F. S. Tun\nper suid that he had carefully examined\nthe place where the body was ioun\nand discovered sleigh track leading\nthere and other theories are that the\nman may have been murdered and take\nthere or murdered after be ins? taken\nthen;. A little distance from where the\nldy was found, the enow had Iteeri\ntrampled down and under the snow were\nblood stums. 1 he tracks led Mist\nshed in a near-by meadow where\nfire had recently been kindled, and\nlittle farther on the track were lost.\nResident of Barre Passed Away at Web\nsterville To-day.\nThe death of James MeConachic oe\ncurred this morning at Websterville\nwhere ho had recently moved from this\ncity, the cause being consumption, Mr,\nMcConachie had been ill for some time\nwith the disease and wont to Webster\nville in the hope that the open-air occn\npat ion nnd the higher altitude would\nprove, of benefit to Ids health. He was\nfor a long time a resident of this city\nand was well known amr respected. He\nleaves a family, consisting of his wife\nand four children. Mrs. McConachie is\nill at this tiriie. Mr. McQmnchie was\namong the first of the Scotch citizens\nfo come to Barre, and follow the occupa\nturn of granite cutter.\nHe was born in Aberdeenshire, Scot\nland, 47 years ago, but had been a rod\ndent of Jlurre for twenty years and more.\nHe was a member of Clan Cordon, O. S.\nC, I'p to recent years he was an athlete\nof considerable abihtv, being a man oi\nlarge frame and powerful physique.\nDEATH OF M. COOK.\nCLEARS COURT FOR\nDAUGHTER'S STORY\nDESERTED AT THE ALTAR.\nBridegroom-to-Be Leaves Pretty Vera\n-White Waiting at City Hall\nBoston. Jan. 29. The bridegroom's\ncourage failed him at the last minute\nyesterday, and he fled, leaving pretty\nVera White of Cambridge alone and un\nwed at City hail. Miss White would not\ntell the name of her delinquent sweet\nheart. When the couple appeared in City hall\nPat rolenmn ?dcllugh consented to as\nsist in arranging the ceremony. Tne\nyoung anan asked t he officer if he could\nfind a room where he could \"slick up\"\na bit in preparation for the ordeal. The\npatiolman produced a brass key and\nthe bridegroom went away.\nHe never came back. The bride went\nhomm broken hearted and the patrolman\nwent to look for the duplicate key.\nMAINE HERDS IMPROVING.\nGeraldine Walker Says Hoxie Was Never\nat the House After Her Father's\nDeath.\nExeter, X. H., Jan. 2!). When Gerald\nine Walker, the 17-year-old daughter of\nthe. defendant in the Hoxie-Walker\nalieniltion suit, took the witness stand\nlestcTday, the. court room was cleared of\n!1 not directly concerned in the ease.\nMis Walker attends school at Briar\ncliir, Yt. She testified that she was at\nhome for ihe Easter vacation of 100\",\nwhich was one-of the periods during\nwhicn witnevsses tor trie pwmtill asserted\nHuxie visited the Walker bouse. Sh\nand her mother were always together\nwhen at home, he suid, and occupied the\nMime room.\nShe never saw Iloxie speak to her\nmother except on business, or sit down\nin thw house, she said. Xor Jwd she\never swm Hoxie at their homo after\nher father's death, a year ago, testified\nthe witness.\nHer brother, Williard, IS years old,\nm his senior year at St. Paul s, corrob\norated her story. Ho said he had never\nseen Hoxie at the house.\nOther witnesses during the day were\nLatayette V. Jewell of Portsmouth, a\nphotographer: William A. (irover of\nPortsmouth; Dr. Austin- W. Blair, Btw\nton, who had attended Mrs. Wsilker and\nher son professionally; and Mrs. Sarah\nF. Kent ot Ohio, sister ot .Mrs. Walker\nCHOKED TO DEATH.\nAlbert Nason Died in a Boston Restaur\nant Last Night.\nBoston, Jan. 20. Albert Xason, aged\n57 veins, a tea and coffee salesman, died i\nas a result of a lit of choking while\neating in a Commercial street restaur\nant last night. He was Imrn in K'-nne-bunkport.\nMe., being the son of a\nwealthy sea captain. He as a brother\nof former Mayor William Xason of\nlViver. N. H. He leaves a wife, who re\nsides in Chicago.\nOnly 4 Per Cent, of the Cattle Found\nDiseased Under Tuberculin Test.\nAugusta, Me.. Jan. 20. A fact grati\nfying to the- dairymen of the state was\nannounced in the annual report yester\nday of the Maine cattle commisrdoners\nto the effect that tiie past yw.r only 4\nper cent, of the cattle examined by the\ntubtvulin test were diseased, whereas in\n100o and 100(1 (i per cent, of the grade\ncattle and 20 per cent, of the pure bloods\ntested with tiibfn-ulin were diseased.\nThe past jcar 2o.imio head were tested\nal MiJ condemned. Sixty-eight horses\nand oli sheep aiso were condemned. The\namount expended for cat tie. horse and\ne.xpc;,e during the year was ?2.\"i.,lt(i.\nThere were over 9,iHiO oattle sold to\nBrighton. M an-1 only to were re\nported ha k to the cuiiiroisskmers as\ntailing to piss the tubpreiilin te.-t.\nNO POLITICS IN IT.\nSay Those Who Are Getting W. H. Taft\nto Speak i Vermont\nSt. AIIhuis, Jan. 20. A statement by\nDr, H. D Holton, Vermont Red Cros\npresident, and W. J. Van Patten, pre-i\ndent of the Vermont Society of the\nSons of the American Revolution as to\nthe mison why an invitation was ex\ntended to. the Hon. William II. Taft,\nnational president of the Red Cross so\nciety, to address the Vermont society\nat its mid-w inter meeting, contains the\nfollowing: \"Any intimation that there\nis anything of poiit-ieal object on the\npart ot tho-e having extended the invi\ntation to Scretary Taft or on his part\nin accepting is wisnllv without founda\ntion and is a gratuitous reflection not\nonly upon Secretary Taft himself as\npresident of the Red (Yoks, but upon\nthe officer of the two organizations.\"\nSecretary Taft's address will be in\nthe interests of tne Red Cross society\nand incidentally on the Sons of the\nAmerican Revolution.\nHe will also