es Kencfick.\nA FAIR YEAR\nFOR BUILDING\nInspector of Buildings Reports\nI 344 Permits Granted\nINCLUDING 14 HOUSES\nAmount Expended Was About the Same\nas For the Year PreviousTempo\nrary Loan of $5,000 Authorized\nby the Council\nGEN. C. H. HOWARD DEAD.\nWas;\nBrother of General 0. 0. Howard\nof Burlington.\nBurlington, Jan. 20.-tieneral 0. O.\nHoward roeeived word yesterday of the\ndeath on Monday of hi brother, General\nCharles If. Howard of Chicago. Early\nin the war for the union, Oenerai Charles\nHoward was assigned to duty as aide-de\ncamp uinm the staff of his brother, and\nfought with great gallantry all through\nthe war, bemg several tunes wounded\nHe receive! many brevets and promo\ntion, and was mustered out witn the\nrank of brigadier-general. General 0\n0. Howard and bis son, H. S. Howard\nleft on the noon train yesterday for\nChics go.\nOFFICERS RE-ELECTED\nBy Montpelier Association of Congre\ngational Ministers.\nThe Mtmtpe'ier Association- of Con\ngregational Ministers held its annual\nmeeting yesterday in the parlors- of the\nM. C. A. at Montpelier. the Rev.\nW. C. Maelntyre of Barre, the Rev.\nFrazer Metr.ger of Randolph and the\nRev. A. M. Smith of Koxbury were ad\nmined to membership. The roiwts of\nthe officers were read and accepted. The\nlev. Donald rnuer of Berlin Corner was\nre-elected president and moderator, and\nthe Rev. D. II. Strong of W illiamstown\na secretary and treasurer.\nRATE CASE ARGUED.\nState vs. Central Vermont R. R. Wll\nin Supreme Court Today.\nIn supreme court today Attorney\nGeneral Fitts argued for the state of\nVermont its ease against the Central\n'ermont railroad, being brought on the\nground of alleged discrimination of\nfreight rates on the transportation oi\ncoal.\nAN ASSORTMENT\nWatered Milk and Liquor Selling Were\nCases in Burlington Court.\nBurlington, Jim. 20. Svlvefiter Sails\nof South Burlington was fined $100 in\nit y court to-day for selling watered\nmilk. John Martelle was lined $300 for\nselling liquor.\nTALK OF THE TOWN\nSWIFT ARRESTED.\nCharged With Having Distributed Circu\nlars on the Street.\nBoston, Jan. Morriicin Sift,\nwhose f pen-air rntetirigs and parades\nhave kept the po'i.e busy for weeks\npast whs sr:-! on the common yes\ntenlay a a warrant accusing him\nvioi at ing the y ordinances by th'ri\nbniiirar circulars without a permit out -side\nthe fnee state employment office on\nKnee is ud ftrcct yetcruay.\nW. W. Hepburn returned to-day from\nTroy, X. V., where he was called -two\nweeks since bv the death of his grand-\nither.\nA man giving hi name as James Hol\nland, drunk and glad of it, was arrested\nthis afternoon by special officer A. J.\nStewart. W hen arrested, he was wan-\nring around the railroad track near\niTospect street.\nAmong arrivals et the City hotel las\neuing and to-day are H. X. Kimlmil,\nEiioxburgh Falls: F. M. t.la.-s. Host on;\nA. .1. Pa wic. C. W. Payne, Burlington;\nF. A. Lt'and. Springfield; Fj A. Dole.\nRoMon M. P. Fisher, Rutland; A. K.\nIliiilsirii. New York; S. W. 1 linden, I5nr\nNneton; S. E. Browned, Burlington; L.\nC. Avian's. Port hind. Me.; M. li. Woiton,\nNew York: C. L. Wilcox. I'.Moh; J. L.\naulfet, W liite River Junction.\nBuilding operation in Barro during\nthe past year were of about tiie same\nmagnitude as those of IDUU both con\nsiderably lower than the record accord\ning to the annual report of tho city in\nspector of buildings, Martin Riley. There\nwere fewer, by sixteen, permits granted.\nbut the difference lit in a lcer num\nber of heiihousos constructed. So that\nthe sum total of money expended in\nbuilding operation was nearly the same.\nIn 1000 there were 3ti0 permits and last\nyear there were 344, representing all\nmanner of work, from shingling a root\nto building a library.\nthe more important were these: single\ntenement houses 14, barns 7, carriage\nhouses 14, store-houtse 2, stono shed 1,\nbusiness- block 1, greenhouse 1, library\n1, ice-house 1, summer-lions 2, hen\nhouse 21. The inspector refused to\ngrant two applications for permit.\nWard three and live were tied for\nfirst place in the number of permit a\ngranted, with 00 each. Ward four bad\n57. The second and sixth wards were\neven with 53 and ward one was last\nwith 45.\nThis report waa presented to the meet\ning of the city council last evening:\nin aduition' to accepting it ami order\ning it printed in the annual city report,\nthe council authorized a temporary Ioun\nof $,i,000 in anticipation of taxes, the\nnote to be payable August 10, 11K18, aad\nat such rate- as shall be satisfactory to\nthe mayor, treasurer and chairman of\nthe nuance committee.\nAnother resolution relating to issuing\nthe city's note to the cemetery commis\nsions was also adopted. Tlie council\npassed a vote that it was their desire\nthat the, city's library books be cata\nlogued with those of tlie Aldrich library,\nwith a distinctive mark Knowing the\nsource.\nSeveral horsemen asked for tlie use of\nlower North Main street for a speedway.\nIt is not likely that tho request will be\ngranted, a that street is imicfa fre\nquented, but another street may be\ngranted for that purpose at certain\ntime.\nTrouble Over Small Piece of Land.\nA matter which was considered in\nexecutive session, but which waa first\nbrought up in open session, was1 sec\nond letter from Henry A. Phelps, rela\ntive to a narrow strip of land on the\nnortherly side of Cottage street, and\nrunning parallel with F, T. Cutler's\nproperty. When Cottage street was\nfixed up last summer, an assessment for\nstreet betterment was levied upon Mr.\nPhelps as owner of a strip eight feet\nwitle on the, Main street and taperinf\noff to a foot-. u\nMr. Phelps- declined to pay the assess\nment. Then comes F. T. Cutler and pay\nthe assessment,, amounting to $22.5S.\nTo the city's acceptance of this amount\nfrom Mr. Cutler and its refusal to pro\nceed against him jtl'hclps) for collect\ning the same, the latter wrote a letter\nof protest to the council on January\n15.\nThis letter was kid on the table, but\nnot, as the members suid last night,\nwith any intent -to be discourteous to\nMr. Phelps.\nMr. Phelps' second letter, which was\nread last night, is- as follows:\nXow as a citizen of iu municipality\na tv-ell asi a. votAr and tavmver I oro-\ntest against such high-handed awl auto\ncratic action on your part.\nIn my communication I requested an\nimmediate answer and action on your\npart, for an act of yours which as I set\nforth in said communication was in\nmy opinion, on your part illegal and un-\njust as well as Eliowing favoritism\nagainst me.\n\"I again respectfully request the city\ncouncil of the city of Barre to take\nimmediate and decisive action en, my\ncommunication of January 18, 1908, and\nto immediately notify mo of said action.\nI can see no good reason if you hava\nacted in good faith and apconBng ta\nyour best, judgment in this matter, why\nyou should not be more than willing to\nratify the former vote referred to by\nstill \"another vote substantiating your\npresent attitude. If, on the other hand,\nvou have overstepped your authority,\nvou should at least be willing to act\nthe part of men and acknowledge it.\nAt all hazards mere is no reason iur\nyour discourtesy in tabling my com\nmunicating and refusing to answer it.\nKindly give me an answer to my tor.\nmer communication referred to at once.\"\nThe council referred the matter to tht\ncity attorney to report, after consider\nable discussion.\nENJOYED JACKSON'S LECTURE.\n\"Charles Dickens, Novelist and Reform\ner\" Well Treated.\nThe lecture last evening in Kellogg-\nlublmrd library hall at Montjielier by\nA. G. Jackson on \"diaries Jhckeiw,\nNovelist and Reformer,\" was a literary\ntreat. Mr. Jack ton was entirely famil\niar with his subject and in vivid lan\nguage he drew a pleasing picture of tloj\nEnglish novelist interspersing it wit!\nextracts from his writings that kept tha\nm.uieuce neenly interested for n hour\nor more. The lecture was the nature of\nan 